@johnsca, @simonklb 

We need to be very careful with putting flag names in variables, because we already use the dot-notation in the names of our flags. Sorry to keep pushing on this, but I think we're about to make a big mistake here.

```python
# these two preconditions are the same
@when(relations.db.flags.changed)
@when('relation.db.changed')

# but these three are invalid
@when(relations.db.changed)
@when(relation.db.flags.changed)
@when('relations.db.flags.changed')

# and these two preconditions might be the same if the interface authors mess up
@when(relations.cassandra.flags.changed)
@when(relations.mysql.flags.changed)
```

This will cause lots of confusion and hard to debug errors. What we need is a single way to reference a flag. The variable name should be the flag name + a prefix.

Would the following proposal help with what you're trying to accomplish?

```python
class MyRelation(SimpleRelation):
    API_FLAGS: [
        'relation.{relation_name}.changed',
        'relation.{relation_name}.ready',
    ]
````

The reactive framework will then add these flags to the context variable so you can do the following.

```python
from charms.reactive.context import flags

@when(flags.relation.db.changed) 
def reconfigure_database():
    db_credentials = relations.db.get_credentials()

# these two are the same
@when("relation.db.changed" )
@when(flags.relation.db.changed)
```

 - Flag conflicts are immediately clear.
 - The public API of a class can still be documented.
 - Typing errors are clearer.
 - The capital case makes it clear that this is static. It's the API of that interface layer you're specifying.

