Actually, there are five implicit calls in methods onCreate() of class _AlertActivity_ of [Dropdialer.apk](https://github.com/ashishb/android-malware/tree/master/BreakBottleneck/SamplesOfHIP2014TalkBreakBottleneck/Dropdialer.A), they are:
`[Lcom/nnew/superMariowallpapers/AlertActivity; onCreate(),
 Landroid/view/View$OnClickListener; onClick]`
`[Lcom/nnew/superMariowallpapers/AlertActivity; onCreate(), 
Landroid/view/View$OnClickListener; onClick]`
`[Lcom/nnew/superMariowallpapers/AlertActivity; onCreate(), Landroid/content/DialogInterface$OnClickListener; onClick]`
`[Lcom/nnew/superMariowallpapers/AlertActivity; onCreate(), Landroid/os/Handler; handleMessage]`
`[Lcom/nnew/superMariowallpapers/AlertActivity; onCreate(), Ljava/lang/Runnable; run]`

These implicit calls are caused by creating a new object using keyword **new**. For instance, the implicit call between onCreate() and  run() is caused by the following code snippet.

```
this.workThread = new Thread(new Runnable() {
            public void run() {
                AlertActivity.this.procedure();
                Log.d("Thread", "end thread");
                AlertActivity.this.handler.sendEmptyMessage(0);
            }
        });
```
In this case, the compiler will generate an auxiliary class like _AlertActivity$5_. So, a solution is to add edges from onCreate() to all methods in auxiliary class  _AlertActivity$5_.

